# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aldolase-c
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 1,3-Bisphosphoglycerate is the conjugate base of 1,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] It is phosphorylated at the number 1 and 3 carbons.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The result of this phosphorylation gives 1,3BPG important biological properties such as the ability to donate a phosphate group to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) in order to form the energy storage molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00118 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 1.2.1.12 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 1,3BPG is a macroergic metabolic intermediate in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] It is created by the exergonic oxidation of the aldehyde in glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The result of this oxidation is the conversion of the aldehyde group into a carboxylic acid group which drives the formation of an acyl phosphate bond.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The latter reaction is the only step in the glycolytic pathway in which NAD+ is converted into NADH.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The formation reaction of 1,3BPG requires the presence of an enzyme called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The high-energy acyl phosphate bond of 1,3BPG is important in respiration as it assists in the formation of ATP.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The molecule of ATP created during the following reaction is the first molecule produced during respiration.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The transfer of an inorganic phosphate from the carboxyl group on 1,3BPG to ADP to form ATP is reversible due to a low ΔG.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This is as a result of one acyl phosphate bond being cleaved whilst another is created.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This reaction is not naturally spontaneous and requires the presence of a catalyst.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This role is performed by the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] During the reaction phosphoglycerate kinase undergoes a substrate induced conformational change similar to another metabolic enzyme called hexokinase.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Because two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate are formed during glycolysis from one molecule of glucose, 1,3BPG can be said to be responsible for two of the ten molecules of ATP produced during the entire process.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Glycolysis also uses two molecules of ATP in its initial stages as a committed and irreversible step.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] For this reason glycolysis is not reversible and has a net produce of 2 molecules of ATP and two of NADH.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The two molecules of NADH themselves go on to produce approximately 3 molecules of ATP each.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 1,3-BPG has a very similar role in the Calvin cycle to its role in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] For this reason both reactions are said to be analogous.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] However the reaction pathway is effectively reversed.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The only other major difference between the two reactions is that NADPH is used as an electron donor in the calvin cycle whilst NAD+ is used as an electron acceptor in glycolysis.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] In this reaction cycle 1,3BPG originates from 3-phosphoglycerate and is made into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate by the action of specific enzymes.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Contrary to the similar reactions of the glycolytic pathway, 1,3BPG in the Calvin cycle does not produce ATP but instead uses it.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] For this reason it can be considered to be an irreversible and committed step in the cycle.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The outcome of this section of the cycle is an inorganic phosphate is removed from 1,3BPG as a hydrogen ion and two electrons are added to the compound+.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] In complete reverse of the glycolytic pathway reaction, the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase catalyses the reduction of the carboxyl group of 1,3BPG to form an aldehyde instead.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This reaction also releases an inorganic phosphate molecule which is subsequently used as energy for the donation of electrons from the conversion of NADPH to NADP+.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Overseeing this latter stage of the reaction is the enzyme glyceraldehyde-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] During normal metabolism in human erythrocytes, ≈19% of the 1,3BPG produced does not go any further in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] It is instead shunted through the Luebering–Rapoport pathway involving the reduction of ATP in the red blood cells.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] During this alternate pathway it is made into a similar molecule called 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid (2,3BPG).
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 2,3BPG is used as a mechanism to oversee the efficient release of oxygen from hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Levels of this 1,3BPG will raise in a patient's blood when oxygen levels are low as this is one of the mechanisms of acclimatization.
[src:aldolase-c/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Low oxygen levels trigger a rise in 1,3BPG levels which in turn raises the level of 2,3BPG which alters the efficiency of oxygen dissociation from hemoglobin.
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] It requires thiamine diphosphate (ThDP) as cofactor.
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] The entry is intended to mainly represent the class of enzymes examplified by human HACL1 (gene), which can catalyze both reactions and is found in the peroxisome.
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] It is required for handling phytanic acid.
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] Humans and other mammals have another similar enzymes that only catalyzes reaction (2) and is instead located in the endoplasmic reticulum, HACL2 (gene).
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] This one participates in phytosphingosine degradation.
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] Both the baker's yeast and the fission yeast have a *Pxp1* gene corresponding to this activity, as annotated on UniProt by sequence similarity (not by experimental characterization of enzyme activity).
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] These two versions are known to appear in the cytoplasm and the peroxisome based on experimental evidence listed in UniProt.
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] Both the mouse-ear cress (Arath) and the rice have a *HACL* gene corresponding to this activity, as annotated on UniProt by sequence similarity (not by experimental characterization of enzyme activity).
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] The Arath version is experimentally detected in the cytoplasm, peroxisome, and plastid.
[src:aldolase-c/2-hydroxyphytanoyl-coa-lyase] UniProt reports that the social ameoba *Dictyostelium discoideum* has a version of this enzyme, as annotated on UniProt by sequence similarity (not by experimental characterization of enzyme activity).
[src:aldolase-c/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] 2-phosphoglyceric acid is an intermediate that is part of the glycolysis pathway, and it is converted into phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) by an enolase.
[src:aldolase-c/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] There are three types of enolase enzymes that are able to catalyze the conversion of 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP, which are alpha-enolase, beta-enolase, and gamma-enolase.
[src:aldolase-c/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Studies have found that Alpha-enolase is the most common enolase, so it is often the specific enolase used to convert 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP.
[src:aldolase-c/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Alpha-enolase catalyzes this conversion process by acting as a Hydrolase, which means that alpha-enolase removes a water molecule from the 2-phosphoglyceric acid in order to form PEP.
[src:aldolase-c/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 4.2.1.11 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/2-phosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00074 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The HMGCL gene encodes a 34.5-kDa protein that is localized to the mitochondrion and peroxisome.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Multible isoforms of the proteins are known due to alternative splicing.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The major isoform (isoform 1) is most highly expressed in the liver whereas isoform 2 is found in energy-demanding tissues including the brain, heart, and skeletal muscle.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Structure of the HMGCL protein has been resolved by X-ray crystallography at 2.1-Å resolution, and reveals that the protein may function as a dimer.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Substrate access to the active site of the HMGCL enzyme involves substrate binding across a cavity located at the C-terminal end of a beta barrel structure.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] In addition, the lysine 48 residue which is mutated in patients with 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA lyase deficiency is also found to be necessary for substrate binding.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Electron density was observed indicating a bound metal ion, presumably Mg2+ due to its inclusion in the crystallization medium.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The enzyme activity is dependent on the presence of the metal this was determined by mutating His233 to Ala233 and Asp42 to Asn42 and experiencing catalytic deficiency of 6.4E−3 kcat/kM and 1.3E−5 kcat/kM respectively.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The substrate binding site includes arginine 41 making a salt bridge to the carboxylate of the hydroxyglutaric acid closest to metal ion.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] A mutation in Arg 41 results in a drastic decrease of catalytic activity.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The extreme decrease in efficiency suggests the direct involvement in the chemistry of the catalytic reaction.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] This Arg41 also salt bridges to Glu72 to fold into the correct position and charge balance Arg41 to bind to the substrate.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] The HMGCL protein plays an essential role in breaking down dietary proteins and fats for energy.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] and requires a divalent metal ion as co-factor.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Deficiency HMG-CoA lyase deficiency causes hypoketotic hypoglycemia similar to that is caused by HMGCS2 mutations but also leads to organic acid accumulation and metabolic acidosis due to altered leucine metabolism.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] This disorder can be mistaken for Reye syndrome because of the symptoms of vomiting, lethargy, and convulsions.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Mutations in the *HMGCL* gene cause 3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-CoA lyase deficiency (HMGCLD), a rare autosomal recessive inborn error of metabolism characterized by disruption of ketogenesis and L-leucine catabolism.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] To-date more than 30 different mutations including missense mutations of different residues have been associated with patients with HMGCLD in diverse families and ethnicities.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] HMGCLD typically presents in the first year of the patient's life after a fasting period.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] Clinical acute symptoms include vomiting, seizures, metabolic acidosis, hypoketotic hypoglycemia, and lethargy.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] HMGCL interacts with itself to form homodimers and homotetramers.
[src:aldolase-c/3-hydroxy-3-methylglutaryl-coa-lyase] It is also shown in yeast two-hybrid experiments to interact with DNAJA1.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:aldolase-c/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] The protein encoded by this gene is a glycolytic enzyme that catalyzes the reversible conversion of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (G3P) and dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP).
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Three aldolase isozymes (A, B, and C), encoded by three different genes, are differentially expressed during development.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Aldolase A is found in the developing embryo and is produced in even greater amounts in adult muscle.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Aldolase A expression is repressed in adult liver, kidney and intestine and similar to aldolase C levels in brain and other nervous tissue.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Aldolase A deficiency has been associated with myopathy and hemolytic anemia.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Alternative splicing and alternative promoter usage results in multiple transcript variants.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Related pseudogenes have been identified on chromosomes 3 and 10.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] ALDOA is a homotetramer and one of the three aldolase isozymes (A, B, and C), encoded by three different genes.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] The *ALDOA* gene contains 8 exons and the 5' UTR IB.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Key amino acids responsible for its catalytic function have been identified.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] The residue Tyr363 functions as the acid–base catalyst for protonating C3 of the substrate, while Lys146 is proposed to stabilize the negative charge of the resulting conjugate base of Tyr363 and the strained configuration of the C-terminal.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Residue Glu187 participates in multiple functions, including FBP aldolase catalysis, acid–base catalysis during substrate binding, dehydration, and substrate cleavage.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Though ALDOA localizes to the nucleus, it lacks any known nuclear localization signals (NLS).
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] In mammalian aldolase, the key catalytic amino acid residues involved in the reaction are lysine and tyrosine.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] The tyrosine acts as an efficient hydrogen acceptor while the lysine covalently binds and stabilizes the intermediates.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Many bacteria use two magnesium ions in place of the lysine.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Compound C05378 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Enzyme 4.1.2.13 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Compound C00111 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] ALDOA is a key enzyme in the fourth step of glycolysis, as well as in the reverse pathway gluconeogenesis.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] It catalyzes the reversible conversion of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to glyceraldehydes-3-phosphate and dihydroxyacetone phosphate by aldol cleavage of the C3–C4 bond.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] As a result, it is a crucial player in ATP biosynthesis.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] ALDOA also contributes to other "moonlighting" functions such as muscle maintenance, regulation of cell shape and motility, striated muscle contraction, actin cytoskeleton organization, and regulation of cell proliferation.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] ALDOA likely regulates actin cytoskeleton remodeling through interacting with cytohesin-2 (ARNO) and Arf6.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] ALDOA is ubiquitously expressed in most tissues, though it is predominantly expressed in developing embryo and adult muscle.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] In lymphocytes, ALDOA is the predominant aldolase isoform.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Within the cell, ALDOA typically localizes to the cytoplasm, but it can localize to the nucleus during DNA synthesis of the cell cycle S phase.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] This nuclear localization is regulated by the protein kinases AKT and p38.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] It is suggested that the nucleus serves as a reservoir for ALDOA in low glucose conditions.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] ALDOA has also been found in mitochondria.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] ALDOA is regulated by the energy metabolism substrates glucose, lactate, and glutamine.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] In human mast cells (MCs), ALDOA has been observed to undergo post-translational regulation by protein tyrosine nitration, which may alter its relative affinity for FBP and/or IP3.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] This change then affects IP3 and PLC signaling cascades in IgE-dependent responses.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Aldolase A (ALDOA) is highly expressed in multiple cancers, including lung squamous cell carcinoma (LSCC), renal cancer, and hepatocellular carcinoma.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] It is proposed that ALDOA overexpression enhances glycolysis in these tumor cells, promoting their growth.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] In LSCC, its upregulation correlates with metastasis and poor prognosis, while its downregulation reduces tumor cell motility and tumorigenesis.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Thus, ALDOA could be a potential LSCC biomarker and therapeutic drug target.
[src:aldolase-c/aldoa] Aldolase A deficiency is a rare, autosomal recessive disorder that is linked to hemolysis and accompanied by weakness, muscle pain, and myopathy.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] In humans, aldolase B is encoded by the *ALDOB* gene located on chromosome 9.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] The gene is 14,500 base pairs long and contains 9 exons.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Defects in this gene have been identified as the cause of hereditary fructose intolerance (HFI).
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] The generic fructose bisphosphate aldolase enzyme cleaves a 6-carbon fructose sugar into two 3-carbon products in a reverse aldol reaction.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] This reaction is typified by the formation of a Schiff base intermediate with a lysine residue (lysine 229) in the active site of the enzyme; the formation of a Schiff base is the key differentiator between Class I (produced by animals) and Class II (produced by fungi and bacteria) aldolases.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] After Schiff base formation, the fourth hydroxyl group on the fructose backbone is then deprotonated by an aspartate residue (aspartate 33), which results in an aldol cleavage.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Schiff base hydrolysis yields two 3-carbon products.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Depending on the reactant, F1P or FBP, the products are DHAP and glyceraldehyde or glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate, respectively.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] The ΔG°’ of this reaction is +23.9 kJ/mol.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Though the reaction may seem too uphill to occur, it is of note that under physiological conditions, the ΔG of the reaction falls to close to or below zero.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] For example, the ΔG of this reaction under physiological conditions in erythrocytes is -0.23 kJ/mol.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Aldolase B is a homotetrameric enzyme, composed of four subunits with molecular weights of 36 kDa with local 222 symmetry.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Each subunit has a molecular weight of 36 kDa and contains an eight-stranded α/β barrel, which encloses lysine 229 (the Schiff-base forming amino acid that is key for catalysis).
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Though the majority of the overall structure of the aldolase enzyme is conserved amongst the three isozymes, four regions of the generic aldolase enzyme have been identified to be highly variable among isozymes.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Such regions have been denoted isozyme-specific regions (ISR1-4).
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] These regions are thought to give isozymes their specificities and structural differences.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] ISRs 1-3 are all found in exon 3 of the *ALDOB* gene.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] ISR 4 is the most variable of the four and is found at the c-terminal end of the protein.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] ISRs 1-3 are found predominantly in patches on the surface of the enzyme.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] These patches do not overlap with the active site, indicating that ISRs may change specific isozyme substrate specificity from a distance or cause the C-terminus interactions with the active site.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] A recent theory suggests that ISRs may allow for different conformational dynamics in the aldolase enzyme that account for its specificity.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Aldolase B plays a key role in carbohydrate metabolism as it catalyzes one of the major steps of the glycolytic-gluconeogenic pathway.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Though it does catalyze the breakdown of glucose, it plays a particularly important role in fructose metabolism, which occurs mostly in the liver, renal cortex, and small intestinal mucosa.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] When fructose is absorbed, it is phosphorylated by fructokinase to form fructose 1-phosphate.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Aldolase B then catalyzes F1P breakdown into glyceraldehyde and DHAP.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] After glyceraldehyde is phosphorylated by triose kinase to form G3P, both products can be used in the glycolytic-gluconeogenic pathway, that is, they can be modified to become either glucose or pyruvate.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Though the mechanism aldolase B regulation is unknown, increased *ALDOB* gene transcription in animal livers has been noticed with an increase in dietary carbohydrates and decrease in glucagon concentration.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Genetic mutations leading to defects in aldolase B result in a condition called hereditary fructose intolerance.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Due to the lack of functional aldolase B, organisms with HFI cannot properly process F1P, which leads to an accumulation of F1P in bodily tissues.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] In addition to being toxic to cellular tissues, high levels of F1P traps phosphate in an unusable form that does not return to the general phosphate pool, resulting in depletion of both phosphate and ATP stores.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] The lack of readily available phosphate causes the cessation of glycogenolysis in the liver, which results in hypoglycemia.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] This accumulation also inhibits gluconeogenesis, further reducing the amount of readily available glucose.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] The loss of ATP leads to a multitude of problems including inhibition of protein synthesis and hepatic and renal dysfunction.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Patient prognosis, however, is good in cases of hereditary fructose intolerance.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] By avoiding foods containing fructose, sucrose, and sorbitol, patients can live symptom-free lives.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] HFI is recessively inherited autosomal disorder.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Approximately 30 mutations that cause HFI have been identified, and these combined mutations result in a HFI frequency of 1 in every 20,000 births.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Mutant alleles are a result of a number different types of mutations including base pair substitutions and small deletions.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] The most common mutation is A149P, which is a guanine to cytosine transversion in exon 5, resulting in the replacement of alanine at position 149 with proline.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] This specific mutant allele is estimated to account for 53% of HFI alleles.
[src:aldolase-c/aldob] Other mutations resulting in HFI are less frequent and often correlated with ancestral origins.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] ALDOC is one of the three aldolase isozymes (A, B, and C), encoded by three different genes.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] The amino acid sequence of ALDOC is highly similar to those of the other isozymes, sharing a 68% identity with ALDOB and 78% identity with ALDOA.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] In particular, the residues Asp33, Arg42, Lys107, Lys146, Glu187, Ser271, Arg303, and Lys229 are all conserved in the active sites of the three isozymes.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] This active site is located in the center of the homotetrameric αβ-barrel structure of these aldolases.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] However, several structural details set ALDOC apart.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] For instance, the Arg303 residue in ALDOC adopts an intermediate conformation between the liganded and unliganded structures observed in the other isozymes.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] Also, the C-terminal region between Glu332 and Lys71 forms a salt bridge with the barrel region that is absent in the A and B isoforms.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] Moreover, the electrostatic surface of ALDOC is more negatively charged, which may serve as an acidic binding site or as a docking site to accommodate the C-terminal conformations.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] Four ALDOC-specific residues (N90, V92, R96 and D100) may be key for ALDOC-specific functions.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] ALDOC is a key enzyme in the fourth step of glycolysis, as well as in the reverse pathway gluconeogenesis.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] It catalyzes the reversible conversion of fructose-1,6-bisphosphate to glyceraldehydes-3-phosphate (G3P), or glyceraldehyde, and dihydroxyacetone phosphate (DHAP) by aldol cleavage.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] As an aldolase, ALDOC putatively also contributes to other "moonlighting" functions, though its exact involvements remain unclear.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] For instance, it binds less tightly to the cytoskeleton than the other isozymes do, likely due to its more acidic pI.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] In addition, ALDOC participates in the stress-response pathway for lung epithelial cell function during hypoxia and in the resistance of cerebellar Purkinje cells against excitotoxic insult.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] ALDOC is ubiquitously expressed in most tissues, though it is predominantly expressed in brain, smooth muscle, and neuronal tissue.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] However, since the ALDOA isoform is co-expressed with ALDOC in the central nervous system (CS), it is suggested that ALDOC contributes to CNS function outside of glycolysis.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] Moreover, its presence within other cell types, such as platelets and mast cells (MCs), may serve as a failsafe in the case that the other predominant aldolase isozymes become inactivated.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] Within cells, it localizes to the cytoplasm.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] This aldolase has been associated with cancer.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] ALDOC is found to be upregulated in the brains of schizophrenia (SCZ) patients.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] Notably, while ALDOC is differentially expressed in the anterior cingulate cortex (ACC) of male SCZ patients, it displays no significant changes in female SCZ patients, indicating that different regulatory mechanisms may be involved in male versus female SCZ patients.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] It is likely that ALDOC is involved in SCZ through its role in glycolysis, which is a central biochemical pathway in SCZ.
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] Furthermore, ALDOC is reported to undergo oxidation in brains affected by mild cognitive impairment (MCI) and Alzheimer's disease (AD).
[src:aldolase-c/aldolase-c] This oxidative modification inhibits ALDOC activity, causing the accumulation of fructose 1,6- bisphosphate and driving the reverse reaction, in the direction of gluconeogenesis rather than glycolysis, thus halting ATP production.
